----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 1: MULTI-AGENT SYSTEM DESIGN\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q1. Walk me through a multi-agent system you've built.\
\
A: In my Test Analysis Framework, I built a LangGraph-based pipeline with distinct agents \'97\
one for log parsing, one for semantic diagnosis, and one for Jira ticket generation. Each agent\
had a defined role and communicated via shared state. The orchestrator decided routing based\
on the output of the previous node. This reduced manual debugging time by 80%.\
\
Example:\
    log_parser_node --> diagnosis_node --> jira_node\
    Each node reads from and writes to a shared AgentState dict.\
    The diagnosis node writes \{"diagnosis": "OOM error", "confidence": 0.92\}\
    and the jira node reads that to auto-fill ticket fields.\
\
---\
\
Q2. How do you decide when to use a single agent vs. multiple agents?\
\
A: Single agent when the task is a focused, single-domain reasoning loop \'97 e.g., summarizing\
a document. Multiple agents when tasks are parallel, require different expertise, or have clear\
handoff boundaries. In my health coach project, I split retrieval, reasoning, and action into\
separate agents because each had distinct tool sets and context requirements. More agents =\
more complexity, so I default to single unless there's a clear reason to split.\
\
Example:\
    Single agent:  "Summarize this incident report" \uc0\u8594  one LLM call, done.\
    Multi-agent:   "Triage this alert" \uc0\u8594 \
                   Agent 1: fetch enrichment data from SIEM\
                   Agent 2: reason over enriched context\
                   Agent 3: create ticket + notify on-call\
\
---\
\
Q3. How do you design agent collaboration \'97 how do agents hand off work?\
\
A: In LangGraph, I model handoffs as edges in the state graph. Each agent node writes its\
output into the shared state dict, and the next node reads from it. For dynamic routing, I use\
conditional edges where a router function inspects state and returns the next node name.\
\
Example:\
    def route(state):\
        if state["confidence"] < 0.7:\
            return "human_review"\
        return "action_node"\
\
    graph.add_conditional_edges("reasoning_node", route)\
\
---\
\
Q4. How do you prevent agents from going into infinite loops?\
\
A: I set a max_iterations counter in the state and check it at the router. If it exceeds the\
limit, I force-route to a fallback or termination node. LangGraph also supports recursion\
limits at the graph level via the config parameter.\
\
Example:\
    def route(state):\
        if state["iterations"] >= 5:\
            return "fallback_node"\
        return "reasoning_node"\
\
    # Also set at graph level:\
    app.invoke(input, config=\{"recursion_limit": 10\})\
\
---\
\
Q5. How would you design a supervisor/orchestrator pattern?\
\
A: The supervisor is a central LLM node that receives the task, decides which sub-agent to\
call next, and evaluates the result. Sub-agents are tools from the supervisor's perspective.\
The supervisor loops until it decides the task is complete or needs escalation.\
\
Example:\
    Supervisor receives: "Investigate alert #4521"\
    \uc0\u8594  calls researcher_agent (fetches SIEM data)\
    \uc0\u8594  calls reasoning_agent (diagnoses root cause)\
    \uc0\u8594  calls action_agent (creates remediation ticket)\
    \uc0\u8594  decides: task complete, exit loop.\
\
---\
\
Q6. How do you handle inter-agent context \'97 what gets passed between agents?\
\
A: Only what's necessary. I keep the shared state lean \'97 avoid dumping full conversation\
history into every node. For long contexts, I summarize or retrieve relevant chunks from\
memory instead of passing raw data. This keeps latency low and avoids token bloat.\
\
Example:\
    Bad:  state["full_log"] = 50000 token raw log file  \uc0\u8592  passed to every node\
    Good: state["log_summary"] = "OOM at line 412, service: auth-svc"\
          state["relevant_chunks"] = top_3_retrieved_snippets\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 2: STATE MANAGEMENT & ORCHESTRATION\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q7. How does state management work in LangGraph?\
\
A: LangGraph uses a TypedDict as the shared state object. Every node receives the full state,\
modifies its relevant keys, and returns the updated slice. The graph merges updates using\
reducers (default is overwrite; you can use add for list accumulation).\
\
Example:\
    class AgentState(TypedDict):\
        messages: Annotated[list, add_messages]\
        diagnosis: str\
        confidence: float\
\
    def diagnosis_node(state: AgentState):\
        result = llm.invoke(state["messages"])\
        return \{"diagnosis": result.content, "confidence": 0.88\}\
\
---\
\
Q8. How do you persist state across sessions?\
\
A: Using a checkpointer. MemorySaver for in-memory (dev/testing), SqliteSaver or\
PostgresSaver for production persistence. Each run gets a thread_id which acts as the\
session key.\
\
Example:\
    app = graph.compile(checkpointer=SqliteSaver(conn))\
\
    # First run\
    app.invoke(\{"messages": [HumanMessage("Investigate alert")]\},\
               config=\{"configurable": \{"thread_id": "session-123"\}\})\
\
    # Resume same session later\
    app.invoke(\{"messages": [HumanMessage("Continue")]\},\
               config=\{"configurable": \{"thread_id": "session-123"\}\})\
\
---\
\
Q9. Explain how you'd manage long-running workflows that span hours or days.\
\
A: Use a persistent checkpointer (Postgres/SQLite) so the graph state survives restarts.\
Pair with interrupt_before on nodes that require async inputs (like waiting for human\
approval or an external API webhook). The graph resumes from the checkpoint once the\
input arrives \'97 no reprocessing from scratch.\
\
Example:\
    Workflow: generate report \uc0\u8594  wait for manager approval \u8594  send to client\
    Step 2 might take 6 hours.\
    Graph pauses at "approval_node" via interrupt_before.\
    When manager approves via UI, app.update_state() is called and graph resumes\
    from exactly where it paused \'97 state fully intact.\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 3: MEMORY ARCHITECTURE\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q10. Explain your memory architecture in the Test Analysis Framework.\
\
A: Three layers:\
- Short-term: in-graph state for current session context\
- Long-term: ChromaDB for past resolutions and historical error patterns\
- Global: FAISS for fast similarity search across the full knowledge base\
\
On each new failure, the agent queries long-term memory first. If a similar resolution exists,\
it reuses it. Otherwise it reasons fresh and stores the new resolution back to memory.\
\
Example:\
    New error: "CUDA out of memory during model inference"\
    \uc0\u8594  Query ChromaDB: finds past resolution "reduce batch size to 16"\
    \uc0\u8594  Agent applies fix directly, skips LLM reasoning\
    \uc0\u8594  Saves 2-3 seconds of inference time per repeat error\
\
---\
\
Q11. What's the difference between short-term and long-term memory in agents?\
\
A: Short-term is within a single run \'97 the messages/state in the current graph execution.\
It's ephemeral. Long-term is cross-run \'97 stored in a vector DB or key-value store, retrieved\
via semantic search. Long-term memory is what lets an agent "remember" resolutions\
from weeks ago.\
\
Example:\
    Short-term: Agent remembers earlier in THIS conversation that the alert was severity P1.\
    Long-term:  Agent remembers that last month, a similar P1 alert on auth-svc\
                was resolved by restarting the token refresh service.\
\
---\
\
Q12. How do you handle memory retrieval quality \'97 what if irrelevant memories are fetched?\
\
A: I use a CrossEncoder reranker after initial retrieval to re-score candidates by actual\
relevance to the query. I also set a similarity threshold \'97 below a certain score, the memory\
is discarded rather than passed to the LLM. This prevents hallucination from noisy context.\
\
Example:\
    Query: "NullPointerException in payment service"\
    Initial retrieval returns 10 docs (some about DB timeouts \'97 not relevant)\
    CrossEncoder rescores \uc0\u8594  top 3 are all NullPointer-related\
    Similarity threshold (0.75) filters out the DB timeout docs\
    LLM only sees the 3 clean, relevant memories\
\
---\
\
Q13. What is semantic caching and when would you use it?\
\
A: Semantic caching stores LLM responses keyed by embedding of the input query. On a new\
query, if a semantically similar query exists in cache (cosine similarity above threshold),\
return the cached response directly \'97 no LLM call. Useful in high-traffic workflows where\
many queries are paraphrases of the same question.\
\
Example:\
    Query 1: "What caused the auth service to go down?"  \uc0\u8594  LLM call \u8594  cached\
    Query 2: "Why did auth-svc fail?"                    \uc0\u8594  cache hit (similarity 0.94)\
                                                         \uc0\u8594  returns cached response instantly\
    Saves ~1-2s latency and LLM cost on repeat queries.\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 4: RETRIEVAL AUGMENTED GENERATION (RAG)\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q14. Describe your RAG pipeline.\
\
A: I've built hybrid RAG using:\
- BM25 for keyword/sparse retrieval\
- Dense embeddings (SentenceTransformers) for semantic retrieval\
- RRF (Reciprocal Rank Fusion) to merge ranked results from both\
- CrossEncoder reranker to score top-k before passing to LLM\
- HyDE for query expansion on cold queries\
\
Example:\
    Query: "connection pool exhausted postgres"\
    BM25 retrieves:   exact keyword match docs (connection, pool, postgres)\
    Dense retrieves:  semantically similar docs (DB saturation, max connections)\
    RRF merges both ranked lists into one unified top-10\
    CrossEncoder picks top-3 most relevant\
    LLM generates answer grounded in those 3 docs\
\
---\
\
Q15. What is HyDE and when is it useful?\
\
A: HyDE (Hypothetical Document Embeddings) \'97 instead of embedding the raw query, you\
ask the LLM to generate a hypothetical answer to the query, then embed that and search.\
Useful when queries are vague or short and direct retrieval quality is poor.\
\
Example:\
    Query:              "k8s pod crash"   \uc0\u8592  too short, poor retrieval\
    HyDE:               LLM generates: "Kubernetes pod crashes are often caused by\
                        OOMKilled events, misconfigured resource limits, or failed\
                        liveness probes..."\
    Embed that text \uc0\u8594  search \u8594  retrieves much richer, relevant documents\
    Better than embedding the 3-word query directly.\
\
---\
\
Q16. How do you evaluate RAG quality?\
\
A: I use RAGAS metrics:\
- Faithfulness: are LLM claims grounded in retrieved context?\
- Answer Relevancy: does the answer address the question?\
- Context Recall: did retrieval fetch the right documents?\
- Context Precision: are the retrieved docs actually useful?\
\
Example:\
    Test case: Q="What is the fix for OOM error?" \
               Expected answer = "Reduce batch size"\
               Retrieved docs = [batch_size_guide, memory_tuning, unrelated_doc]\
    \
    Faithfulness:      Did LLM say "reduce batch size"? \uc0\u10003 \
    Context Precision: Was unrelated_doc in top results? \uc0\u10007  \u8594  improve retrieval\
    This tells you exactly which part of the pipeline to fix.\
\
---\
\
Q17. How do you chunk documents for a RAG pipeline?\
\
A: Depends on the document type. For logs/structured text, fixed-size chunks with overlap.\
For narrative documents, semantic chunking (SemanticChunker) which splits on topic\
boundaries rather than arbitrary token counts.\
\
Example:\
    Fixed chunking (logs):\
        chunk_size=512, overlap=50  \uc0\u8594  consistent, predictable for structured data\
\
    Semantic chunking (runbooks):\
        Splits on topic shift: "Setup" section stays together,\
        "Troubleshooting" section stays together \'97\
        not cut mid-paragraph just because token limit was hit.\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 5: HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP (HITL)\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q18. How did you implement HITL in your projects?\
\
A: Using LangGraph's interrupt_before mechanism. The graph pauses before a specified node,\
surfaces the agent's output to an SME via Gradio UI. The SME reviews, edits if needed,\
and resumes the graph with app.update_state() + app.invoke() using the same thread_id.\
\
Example:\
    app = graph.compile(checkpointer=MemorySaver(), interrupt_before=["validate_node"])\
\
    # Graph pauses here \'97 SME sees proposed diagnosis in Gradio UI\
    # SME approves or edits, then:\
    app.update_state(config, \{"validated_output": sme_approved_text\})\
    app.invoke(None, config)  # graph resumes from validate_node\
\
---\
\
Q19. When should HITL be triggered in a production agent?\
\
A: Trigger HITL when:\
- Confidence score is below threshold\
- Action is irreversible (deleting data, executing a command, creating a ticket)\
- The task involves sensitive data or compliance scope\
- It's the first time a new error pattern is encountered\
\
Example:\
    Auto-approve:  agent summarizes an incident report        \uc0\u8594  low risk, no HITL\
    HITL required: agent proposes to restart a prod database  \uc0\u8594  irreversible, pause for human\
\
---\
\
Q20. How do you balance automation with control in sensitive environments?\
\
A: I use a tiered autonomy model:\
- Low-risk actions (read, query, summarize) \uc0\u8594  fully automated\
- Medium-risk (create ticket, send alert) \uc0\u8594  automated with audit log\
- High-risk (execute remediation, modify config) \uc0\u8594  HITL required\
\
Example:\
    SOC agent triage flow:\
    Tier 1: Fetch alert + enrich context          \uc0\u8594  automated\
    Tier 2: Create Jira ticket with diagnosis     \uc0\u8594  automated + logged\
    Tier 3: Block IP / isolate endpoint           \uc0\u8594  HITL checkpoint, SOC analyst approves\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 6: TOOL CALLING & INTEGRATIONS\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q21. How does tool calling work in LangChain/LangGraph?\
\
A: Tools are Python functions decorated with @tool. They're bound to the LLM with\
.bind_tools(). The LLM returns a tool_call in its response specifying the tool name and\
arguments. ToolNode executes the function and returns the result as a ToolMessage.\
\
Example:\
    @tool\
    def search_logs(query: str) -> str:\
        """Search historical logs for a given error pattern."""\
        return vector_db.search(query)\
\
    llm_with_tools = llm.bind_tools([search_logs])\
    # LLM decides when to call search_logs based on the query context\
\
---\
\
Q22. How do you handle tool failures gracefully?\
\
A: I configure ToolNode with handle_tool_errors=True. This catches exceptions and returns\
an error message as a ToolMessage instead of crashing the graph. The LLM then decides\
whether to retry, use a fallback tool, or escalate.\
\
Example:\
    tool_node = ToolNode(tools, handle_tool_errors=True)\
\
    # If search_logs raises a timeout exception:\
    # Instead of crash \uc0\u8594  LLM receives:\
    # ToolMessage: "Error: search_logs timed out after 5s"\
    # LLM responds: "Retrying with a narrower query..."\
\
---\
\
Q23. How would you integrate an agent with a third-party security tool like a SIEM?\
\
A: I'd wrap the SIEM's REST API as a LangChain tool. The tool handles auth, constructs\
the query, calls the endpoint, and returns structured results. The agent treats it like any\
other tool \'97 calls it when needed, parses the output, and reasons on top of it.\
\
Example:\
    @tool\
    def query_siem(alert_id: str) -> dict:\
        """Fetch alert details from SIEM by alert ID."""\
        response = requests.get(\
            f"\{SIEM_URL\}/alerts/\{alert_id\}",\
            headers=\{"Authorization": f"Bearer \{API_KEY\}"\}\
        )\
        return response.json()\
\
    # Agent call: query_siem("ALT-9921")\
    # Returns: \{"severity": "critical", "source_ip": "10.0.1.4", ...\}\
\
---\
\
Q24. You integrated Jira in your project \'97 how did that work?\
\
A: I wrapped the Jira REST API as a tool. After the agent diagnosed a log failure, it called\
the create_ticket tool with structured fields \'97 summary, description, priority, suggested fix.\
The tool hit the Jira API and returned the ticket URL stored in state and surfaced to the user.\
\
Example:\
    @tool\
    def create_jira_ticket(summary: str, description: str, priority: str) -> str:\
        """Create a Jira ticket and return its URL."""\
        payload = \{"summary": summary, "description": description,\
                   "priority": \{"name": priority\}\}\
        response = requests.post(JIRA_URL, json=payload, headers=AUTH_HEADERS)\
        return response.json()["self"]\
\
    # Agent output: "Ticket created: https://jira.company.com/browse/OPS-412"\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 7: FAULT TOLERANCE & RELIABILITY\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q25. How do you make agent workflows fault-tolerant?\
\
A: Four layers:\
1. Tool-level: handle_tool_errors=True + retry with backoff\
2. Node-level: try/except inside nodes, write error info to state\
3. Graph-level: conditional fallback edges when confidence is low or errors occur\
4. System-level: persistent checkpointing so crashed runs can resume\
\
Example:\
    Node-level:\
        def diagnosis_node(state):\
            try:\
                result = llm.invoke(state["messages"])\
                return \{"diagnosis": result.content\}\
            except Exception as e:\
                return \{"diagnosis": None, "error": str(e)\}\
\
    Graph-level:\
        def route(state):\
            if state.get("error"):\
                return "fallback_node"\
            return "action_node"\
\
---\
\
Q26. What's your approach to observability in agent systems?\
\
A: I log every node's input/output, tool calls, latency, and token usage. For production I'd\
use OpenTelemetry to trace the full agent execution path. LangSmith is also useful for\
LangChain/LangGraph \'97 it captures every LLM call, tool call, and state transition.\
\
Example:\
    Without observability: agent fails silently, you don't know which node caused it.\
    With LangSmith tracing:\
        Run trace shows:\
        diagnosis_node  \uc0\u8594  1.2s, 800 tokens \u10003 \
        tool: query_siem \uc0\u8594  4.8s TIMEOUT \u10007   \u8592  bottleneck identified immediately\
        fallback_node   \uc0\u8594  triggered\
\
---\
\
Q27. How do you handle hallucination risk in production agents?\
\
A: Three approaches:\
1. Ground every claim in retrieved context \'97 don't let the LLM generate unsupported facts\
2. Use structured output (Pydantic schemas) to constrain what the LLM can return\
3. Validate LLM output against known schemas or tool results before acting on it\
\
Example:\
    Instead of:  llm.invoke("What is the fix?")  \uc0\u8592  free-form, can hallucinate\
    Use:\
        class DiagnosisOutput(BaseModel):\
            root_cause: str\
            confidence: float\
            suggested_fix: str\
            source_doc_id: str   \uc0\u8592  forces LLM to cite a source\
\
        llm.with_structured_output(DiagnosisOutput).invoke(prompt)\
        # If source_doc_id doesn't exist in our DB \uc0\u8594  flag as hallucination\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 8: FEDERATED LEARNING (FROM RESUME)\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q28. What is Federated Learning and what did you build with it?\
\
A: FL trains a shared model across distributed nodes without centralizing raw data. Each node\
trains locally, sends only model updates to an aggregator, which merges them. In my health\
coach project, I used OpenFL to enable hospitals to collectively improve the model without\
sharing patient records.\
\
Example:\
    Traditional ML:  Hospital A sends patient data to central server \uc0\u8594  privacy risk\
    Federated ML:    Hospital A trains locally \uc0\u8594  sends only weight updates\
                     Hospital B trains locally \uc0\u8594  sends only weight updates\
                     Aggregator merges updates \uc0\u8594  improved global model\
                     No raw patient data ever leaves the hospital.\
\
---\
\
Q29. What was the straggler mitigation work you did?\
\
A: In distributed FL, stragglers are slow nodes that delay each training round. I redesigned\
the aggregation strategy to not wait for all nodes \'97 aggregate once a threshold percentage\
of nodes report back (e.g., 80%). Slow nodes are deprioritized in the next round.\
\
Example:\
    Without mitigation:  10 nodes, 1 slow node \uc0\u8594  entire round waits 5 extra minutes\
    With mitigation:     Aggregate when 8/10 nodes report back (80% threshold)\
                         Round completes on time, slow node catches up in next round\
                         Per-round latency reduced by ~60%.\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 9: CYBERSECURITY / SRE USE CASES\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q30. How would you design an agent for incident root cause analysis?\
\
A: Pipeline:\
1. Ingest alert \uc0\u8594  enrich with asset/service metadata via tools\
2. Retrieve similar past incidents from long-term memory (RAG)\
3. Correlate with recent deployment events, config changes via API tools\
4. LLM reasons over enriched context \uc0\u8594  produces ranked RCA hypotheses\
5. Route to automated runbook if confidence is high, else HITL for SRE review\
6. Log decision + outcome for future memory\
\
Example:\
    Alert: "auth-svc latency > 2s"\
    Step 2: RAG finds similar incident from 3 weeks ago \uc0\u8594  "caused by DB connection pool exhaustion"\
    Step 3: Checks deployment logs \uc0\u8594  new release was pushed 10 mins before alert\
    Step 4: LLM hypothesis: "New release likely introduced connection leak. Confidence: 0.89"\
    Step 5: Confidence > 0.85 \uc0\u8594  auto-trigger runbook: restart auth-svc pod\
\
---\
\
Q31. How would you approach runbook automation with agents?\
\
A: Runbooks are structured as tool sequences. I'd represent each runbook step as a tool,\
with preconditions checked before execution. The agent selects the right runbook via RAG,\
then executes steps sequentially with state tracking. Irreversible steps get HITL checkpoint.\
\
Example:\
    Runbook: "Restart auth-svc"\
    Step 1: check_pod_status("auth-svc")          \uc0\u8594  tool call, read-only \u10003  auto\
    Step 2: cordon_node("node-42")                \uc0\u8594  tool call, reversible \u10003  auto\
    Step 3: delete_pod("auth-svc-pod-7x9kl")      \uc0\u8594  irreversible \u8594  HITL pause\
    SRE approves \uc0\u8594  Step 3 executes \u8594  Step 4: verify_pod_healthy() \u8594  done\
\
---\
\
Q32. How do you handle security and compliance in agent systems?\
\
A: Key controls:\
- Least-privilege tool access \'97 each agent only has access to tools it needs\
- Audit logging of every tool call and decision with timestamp and user context\
- Input/output guardrails to prevent prompt injection or sensitive data leakage\
- HITL before any write/execute action in sensitive environments\
- Secrets managed via env vars / vault \'97 never hardcoded in agent logic\
\
Example:\
    Read-only agent (triage):   tools = [query_siem, search_kb, get_asset_info]\
    Action agent (remediation): tools = [create_ticket, restart_pod, block_ip]\
    These are separate agents with separate tool scopes \'97 the triage agent\
    physically cannot call restart_pod even if prompted to do so.\
\
---\
\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
SECTION 10: GENERAL / BEHAVIORAL\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q33. How do you evaluate whether an agentic workflow is production-ready?\
\
A: I check:\
- Task success rate on a held-out eval set\
- Latency per run (p50, p95)\
- HITL intervention rate (high = model not confident enough)\
- Failure mode coverage \'97 every failure path has a defined handler\
- Auditability \'97 full trace of every decision available\
- Guardrails tested against adversarial inputs\
\
Example:\
    Before shipping my log analysis agent:\
    - Ran 200 test log cases \uc0\u8594  91% resolved correctly (threshold was 90%) \u10003 \
    - p95 latency: 4.2s (acceptable for async use case) \uc0\u10003 \
    - HITL rate: 12% (reasonable \'97 only truly ambiguous cases escalated) \uc0\u10003 \
    - Injected malformed logs and prompt injection attempts \uc0\u8594  all handled \u10003 \
    \uc0\u8594  Approved for production.\
\
---\
\
Q34. Walk me through how you'd go from a messy operator workflow to a production agent.\
\
A: \
1. Shadow the operator \'97 understand actual steps, decision points, and edge cases\
2. Map the workflow as a flowchart \'97 identify nodes, branches, tools needed\
3. Identify what needs LLM reasoning vs. what's deterministic\
4. Build a minimal LangGraph prototype with mocked tools\
5. Swap in real tools, test on real data\
6. Add HITL at high-risk nodes, add evals, instrument observability\
7. Run in shadow mode (agent suggests, human acts) before full autonomy\
8. Promote to production once success rate and safety criteria are met\
\
Example:\
    Messy workflow: SOC analyst manually copies alert from SIEM into Slack,\
                    googles the IP, checks if it's in threat intel DB, writes a\
                    summary, and posts it to a ticket.\
    \
    Productized:    Agent auto-fetches alert \uc0\u8594  tool calls SIEM + threat intel API\
                    \uc0\u8594  LLM writes summary \u8594  auto-creates ticket. \
                    What took 15 mins now takes 20 seconds.\
\
---\
\
Q35. What's your approach to prompt engineering for agents?\
\
A: I treat prompts like code \'97 versioned, tested, iterated. Key practices:\
- Concrete examples > abstract descriptions in system prompts\
- Explicit output schema with a JSON example, not just field descriptions\
- Separate system prompt (role/context) from task prompt (current input)\
- Test prompt changes against an eval set before shipping\
\
Example:\
    Bad system prompt:\
        "Return a JSON with root_cause, confidence, and fix fields."\
\
    Good system prompt:\
